observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct a semestral physical count of supplies and materials and submit a copy of the RPCIs per type of inventory to the accounting office, copy furnish to the Audit Team;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to:
Prepare RISs for the issuance of inventory items to end users, summarize through the SSMI and submit the same to the Accounting Office supported with RISs on a weekly basis;
Prepare and maintain stock cards for each item of inventory.
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
Maintain Ledger Cards and to compute the inventory costs using the Moving Average Cost, or the unit cost from its latest purchase, if moving average cost per unit cannot be determined;
Submit a copy of the JEVs pertaining to the recognition of expenses for each of the inventory items, together with the RISs duly signed by the end-users/recipients, to the audit team; and
Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the RPCI and other property records with the books of accounts and to make the necessary adjustments or corrections for a fair presentation of the accounts in the Financial Statements.

We recommended and Management agreed that:
The Municipal Treasury Office and the Inventory Committee exert utmost efforts to:
Conduct physical count of the Real Properties not included in the RPCPPE amounting to  ₱111,943,206.66;
Locate the properties amounting to ₱8,892,034.43 and account for missing items, if any;
Coordinate with the Municipal Accounting Office for the reconciliation of properties with different acquisition cost between accounting and property records amounting to ₱2,438,598.29;
Warrant that PPE classification in the property records is the same as the accounting records; and
Ensure that the property numbers in the RPCPPE are accurate to aid in the reconciliation with accounting records.
The Municipal Accounting Office:
Provide a detailed breakdown of unaccounted balance tagged as beginning balances of the various PPE accounts amounting to ₱19,300,206.66;
Intensify efforts to clear the “for reconciliation/unaccounted” balances in the total amount of ₱464,215.15. Should all efforts to account the same proved futile, consider request for authority to  drop them from the books of the affected PPE accounts; and
Prepare the necessary entries to recognize the unrecorded PPE amounting to ₱9,527,175.19 in the books of accounts.

We recommended and the:
Municipal Treasury Office and the Inventory Committee agreed to include the cost of Local Road Networks in the  Report on Local Road Network and the Report on Physical Count of the Road Network System, respectively;
Municipal Engineer agreed to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer with the complete description and cost segregation of the road components for road projects;
Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Recognize at fair value local roads that were identified without corresponding cost;
Prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation of each depreciable Local Road Network component;
Maintain subsidiary ledgers for the Road Network and their components; and
Provide adequate disclosure for the total Road Network System in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require the BAC to:
Submit the missing attachments/supporting documents;
Invite NGO, COA and private group representative at least five calendar days before the date of eligibility checking, shortlisting, pre-bid conference, bid evaluation and post-qualification; and
Conduct pre-procurement conference pursuant to Section 20 of the Revised IRR of RA 9184;
We also recommended and the Municipal Engineer agreed to:
Adopt the prescribed format of Approved Contract in DPWH D.O. 197 series 2016;
Prepare and include PERT/CPM as part of the contract submitted to the Audit Team; and
Prepare and include minimum requirements for a Construction Safety and Health Program for the project being considered;
We further recommended and the Accountant agreed to ensure the completeness of supporting documents prior to processing of claims.

We recommended that:

a) The Municipal Treasury Office exert utmost efforts to:
i. Conduct an inventory of the Real Properties not included in the RCPPE totaling ₱73,871,954.06; 
ii. Locate the properties amounting to ₱2,666,328.43;
iii. Coordinate with the Municipal Accounting Office for the reconciliation of properties with different acquisition cost between accounting and property records amounting to ₱3,113,694.04; 
iv. Warrant that PPE Classification is the same between the property and accounting records; and
v. Ensure that the property numbers in the RPCPPE are accurate to aid in the reconciliation with accounting records.


b) The Municipal Accounting Office to:

i. Intensify their efforts to account the details of the “for reconciliation/unaccounted” balances in the total amount of ₱471,548.64. Should all efforts to account the same proved futile, consider the dropping them from the books of the affected PPE accounts; and
ii. Prepare the necessary entries to recognize the unrecorded PPE in the books of accounts.

Recommendation/s:
a. For the property officer/Municipal Treasurer, to maintain a central record to be
utilized not only during the inventory taking but also to serve as an internal control system of the custody and responsibility over the properties of the agency;
b. Require the employees accountable for the property claimed to be unserviceable to return the same to the supply officer for disposal;
c. Commence disposal procedures, if warranted, for these unserviceable properties in accordance with rules and procedures in the disposal of properties; and,
d. Provide all Municipal properties with inventory stickers/tags.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following courses of action:
The Municipal Treasurer to open a separate Special Trust Fund bank account for the DRRM funds and deposit the available balance of the QRF and MF (MOOE);
The Municipal Accountant to maintain a record of the continuing appropriations showing the amount and details of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF, which shall be disclosed in the Notes to the Financial Statements following the sample disclosure in the Annex D of COA Circular No. 2012-002.

We recommended and management agreed on the following remedial measures:
The MRHU to provide the MAccO copies of the IRPs so that the drugs and medicines, medical, dental and laboratory supplies, other supplies and PPE received from DOH will be recognized in the books of the Municipality;
The MRHU to prepare a report on the utilization of the commodities received from DOH-CAR duly supported with distribution lists and acknowledgment receipts to be forwarded to the Municipal Accountant as his basis in recognizing inventory items issued in the books of accounts, copy furnished the Audit Teams of the Municipality and DOH-CAR.

We recommended and management agreed that the preparation and approval of the APP to consider the following factors:
The APP should include all procurement activities planned for the year. The approved APP shall be the basis for the Procuring Entity’s procurement, and only those projects/procurement included therein shall be undertaken;
The APP shall include only those procurements that are considered crucial to the efficient discharge of government functions. Procurement is crucial if it is required for the day-to-day operations of the Procuring entity; or it is in pursuit of the principal mandate of the Procuring Entity concerned;
Scheduling of procurement activities should be done in such a manner that the BAC and the other offices/units involved in the procurement process are able to efficiently manage the conduct of procurement transactions.  Moreover, it is paramount that project implementation timelines are met.
